subsection.p:
Therefore, the solutions to the original equation \ 2\sin^2(\theta) + \sin(\theta)  = 0 \  are

         \theta \amp = \pi k, \amp\amp 

         \theta \amp = \frac{7\pi}{6}+2\pi k, \amp\amp \text{and} 

         \theta \amp = \frac{11\pi}{6} + 2\pi k \amp\amp \text{ where } k \text{ is any integer}

solution.p:
Using symmetry, the other solution set for \cos(\theta)=\frac{1}{2} has base angle -\frac{\pi}{3}, which gives
         \theta = -\frac{\pi}{3} + 2\pi k \hspace{.25in} \text{ where } k \text{ is any integer}. 
      Finally, we need to determine which solutions lie in the interval 0\le\theta\le 2\pi. We will do this by constructing a table of k-values, starting at k=0 and increasing k until we are outside of the interval, and then at k=-1 and descreasing until we are outside of the interval.


            

                k
                First solution
                Second solution

            

                k
                \theta=\dfrac{\pi}{3}+2\pi k
                \theta=-\dfrac{\pi}{3}+2\pi k



                0
                \dfrac{\pi}{3} \ \alert{\checkmark}
                -\dfrac{\pi}{3}



                1
                \dfrac{7\pi}{3}
                \dfrac{5\pi}{3} \ \alert{\checkmark}



                2
                \dfrac{13\pi}{3}
                \dfrac{1\pi}{3}









                -1
                -\dfrac{5\pi}{3}
                -\dfrac{7\pi}{3}


        Notice that one value of k can yield a solution for one solution set and a non-solution for the other solutions set! From the table above, we can see that there are exactly two solutions to the original equation 3\sec^2(\theta)-5\sec(\theta)=2 in the interval [0,2\pi]:
